(897, 161, '2015-12-16 00:19:17', '2015-12-16 00:19:17', '<div class="body-journal">\r\n<div class="journal-content">\r\n<p class="journal-inner"><span class="drop-cap">After</span>\r\nan off-road wine filled trip through the Chianti region of Italy (think Napa valley with hand made signs and no paved roads), the next GPS way point was set to the port city of Porto Venere; a small city on the north west side of the “boot”.  Arriving in a tiny, but very “efficient”, cinquecento covered in Tuscan sand and dirt, I handed the Fiat to the valet driver whose skill is akin to fitting the square peg in the round hole.  </p>\r\n<p class="journal-inner">I digress. Porto Venere is a place where no car is desired because it can be walked in a matter of hours, a port city where you actually connect with a local crowd. Absent and drowned of heavy tourism and loud noises, the multicolor hand painted buildings touch the sea wall.  I was captured immediately and thrilled to be spending the weekend.</p>\r\n<p class="journal-inner">I walked aimlessly with my trusted partner *#TBT film Leica M6* and captured as much as I could.  They say (read Wikipedia) the name, Portovenere, comes from the goddess Venus where the church of Peter the Apostle now stands.</p>\r\n<p class="journal-inner">Walking up to the church is an adventure and has some great detours (hint: bring your swimwear).  Just before reaching the top, you can go to the rock formed beach and just relax on one of the ledges or have a very adventures (and cold) swim.</p>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n', 'THE HIDDEN "6th" LAND', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '888-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-12-16 00:19:17', '2015-12-16 00:19:17', '', 888, 'http://dev.hungrylemur.com/888-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
